Perhaps, but digging into the spec, I see (p49): "Note that when determining equality [of dates], these semantics imply that if either date/time has unspecified components, the result of the comparison will be unknown [null]." In the above situation, since the **right** interval is more fully specified than the **left** it seems appropriate that _compareTo(..)_ returns **null**.

Jumping up a level to the calling `IncludedInEvaluator.included(..)`, the spec (p54) says: "Each of these operators [including _IncludedIn_] returns true if the intervals X and Y are in the given relationship to each other. If either or both arguments are null, the result is null. Otherwise, the result is false.". So this leads me to believe that lines 44-45:
```
            return (LessOrEqualEvaluator.lessOrEqual(rightStart, leftStart)
                    && GreaterOrEqualEvaluator.greaterOrEqual(rightEnd, leftEnd));
```
Are not correctly dealing with the fact than `LessOrEqualEvaluator.lessOrEqual(rightStart, leftStart)` can, and in this instance does, return **null**. Throwing an NPE isn't correct behavior. I believe that a correct implementation would be:
```
            Boolean startCompare = LessOrEqualEvaluator.lessOrEqual(rightStart, leftStart);
            Boolean endCompare = GreaterOrEqualEvaluator.greaterOrEqual(rightEnd, leftEnd);
            if (startCompare == null || endCompare == null)
                return null;
            else
                return (startCompare && endCompare);
```
Of course, in this example, still it begs the question of why the CQL `"PeriodToIntervalOfDT"` and `"Assessment Period Three"` are returning incompatible Intervals.

