That is complicated by the fact that there's exclusive choice either I cal "text" once or "addElement" multiple times, this leads to the need of deferring creating body instance builder of Simple or Complex type. One ugly, but working way is to have intermediate modifiable object object

```java
@Value.Immutable(builder=false)
public abstract class Entity {
  @Value.Parameter  public abstract Body getBody();
  interface Body {}
  @Value.Immutable
  public static abstract class SimpleBody implements Body {
    public abstract String getText();
  }
  @Value.Immutable
  public static abstract class ComplexBody implements Body {
    public abstract List<String> getElements();
  }
  @Value.Modifiable
  abstract class BodyBuilder { // Can use styles to customize names & prefixes
      public abstract Optional<String> getText();
      public abstract List<String> getElements();
      public Entity toEntity() {
          checkState(getText().isEmpty() ^ getElements().isEmpty(), "Explain it")
          return ImmutableEntity.of(!getText().isEmpty()
                 ?  ImmutableSimpleBody.of(getText().get())
                  :  ImmutableComplexBody.builder().addAllElements(getElements()).build());
      }
  }
}

Entity simpleBodyEntity = ModifiableBodyBuilder.create()
     .setText("Simple") // prefix in styles `set=`
     .toEntity();

Entity complexBodyEntity = ModifiableBodyBuilder.create()
     .addElement("El1")
     .addElement("El2")
     .toEntity();
```

The simpler way is just create shortcuts to create entities with different kinds of bodies

```
