From the parser's point of view, it was able to match the input to a positional parameter: there is a `@Parameter` field defined that covers position 0 (the position of the first parameter `2-4`). 

`@Unmatched` will only be populated with unknown options, and positional parameters out of range. For example:

```java
class App {
    @Parameters(index = "0") int first;
    @Parameters(index = "1") int second;
    @Parameters(index = "2") int third;
    @Unmatched String[] remainder;
}
```
When you give this app the following input: `0 1 2 3 4` it will put `"3"` and `"4"` in the `remainder` field.

For the purposes of your application, since you want to handle input of mixed type (simple scalar values as well as range values) I would simply catch all positional parameters in a `String` collection and do the type conversion in the application.

